The SEM/EDS (model JSM-6700F) was also used on an SEM (EVO MA15) system to investigate the morphology, element contents of Cu-CQDs films for different immersion times. A three-dimensional laser microscopy (model VK-X100K, KEYENCE) was used to measure the surface roughness of films on a VK_H1XAC_350 analyzer system. A contact angle surface wettability tester (model JC2000DM) was conducted to measure the surface wetting angle with an JC2000 automatic measurement system to obtain the surface wetting angle of films. The surface roughness of the pure steel disc in Table 1
                         is 0.106 μm, the surface wetting angle is 90° (in Fig. 3
                        ), and the main elements and contents of the surface are carbon (4.24 wt%), chromium (1.41 wt%) and iron (94.34 wt%) elements (in Table 1), respectively. When steel discs were immersed into the 0.5 wt% Cu-CQDs solution for different times, the copper content of films were detected obviously increased compared to the pure steel disk. The increase of copper contents is 3.25 wt% for immersion 0.5 h, and 49.88 wt% for immersion 1 h, and 58.97 wt% for 2 h immersion as shown in Table 1. These results indicated that the Cu-CQDs took part in formation of the films on the surface of steel discs. Besides, surface wetting angle of 98° for the immersion 0.5 h film, and increase of 8.8% relative to the pure steel disc, and surface roughness of 0.449 μm. Partial magnification shows that the film is incomplete and there are a few micro-pores as shown in Fig. 3(0.5 h immersion). After soaking for 1 h, the surface wetting angle is 113.5°, which increases by 26.1% compared with that of pure steel disc. Surface roughness of 0.829 μm in Table 1. For immersion 2 h, the surface wetting angle was 93°, which increased by 3.3% relative to the pure steel disc, the surface roughness was 0.704 μm in Table 1.

Table 7
 shows the SEM analysis of worn discs and steel balls lubricated with pure water. The SEM image of the steel disc shows that water lubrication leads to obvious material peeling, the peeling area is visible after magnification, and there is a wide plough furrow. The morphology and EDS analysis of wear marks on the surface of thin film on the steel disc (film for immersion 0.5 h) and steel ball under pure water lubrication. There is obvious flaking of surface film on the surface of the steel disc, and the friction region can be detected without copper elements (in Table 8
), implying that the friction-induced Cu-CQDs film has been completely stripped. The presence of this copper element (1.28 wt% in Table 8) in the surface EDS analysis of the steel balls indicates that the stripped film is partially transferred to the surface of the steel balls for anti-wear and friction reduction, which is the main reason why the friction coefficient and wear rate of the steel discs protected by the film are lower compared to pure water lubrication.
